The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Naveen tours marooned villages
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     Naveen tours marooned villages
          OUR BUREAU                          Naveen Patnaik talks to villagers at a relief camp in Balianta block in Kula Sahi near Bhubaneswar on Friday. Picture by Sanjib Mukherjee                                  
	Bhubaneswar, Sept. 26: Over 1.30 lakh people in 740 villages are still marooned even as the water level in most of the rivers receded.        
	Officials supervising flood relief operations claimed that relief had reached all affected villages.         
	State disaster mitigation secretary G.V.V. Sharma said even the marooned villages had been covered under the relief operations.         
	The railways also decided to transport relief material free of cost across Orissa. Relief material can be booked by any government or private organisation, including NGOs, said a release issued by East Coast Railway, adding that this decision would be implemented with immediate effect.        
	East Coast Railway general manager A.K. Goyal advised all railway staff to accord top most priority to the transport of relief material. The relief parcels are required to be booked in the name of respective district collectors or the special relief commissioner and can be booked from any railway station of the country, said East Coast Railway officials.        
	Chief minister Naveen Patnaik, who visited the flood-hit areas of Balianta block today, later reviewed the relief operation. He was informed that 4 lakh tonnes of rice and other food material had been sent to the flood-affected areas for distributing relief for 15 days.        
	Underscoring the need for providing special assistance to the affected farmers during the time of distress, Naveen directed officials to prepare a special relief package for them. The package would include seeds and revival of damaged lift irrigation points.        
	Naveen also laid stress on expeditious restoration of damaged infrastructure. A sum of Rs 100 crore was released to the water resources department, Rs 60 crore to the works department and Rs 56 crore to the rural development department to undertake restoration and reconstruction work.        
	According to official figures, 2,115 roads are affected by the flood, while 459 breaches have been caused on river embankments. An estimated Rs 340 crore was needed for restoration of damaged roads and other things to pre-flood situation. According to information available with the state disaster management department, more than 41.34 lakh people in 6,382 villages of 19 districts have been hit by the present flood.        
	Meanwhile, the official toll has gone up to 61. According to the latest reports, more than 1.35 lakh houses have been damaged, while standing crop in 4.62 lakh hectares have been affected. The flood has also hit more than 14.42 lakh cattle population.                                                                                                                                                                         
